    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Wanted: Older Workers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Michael S Rabin, New York City's Deputy Commissioner for the Aging, comments on June 21 Business Day article on hiring of older workers; says older top-level executives are not only mature workers currently in demand (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Older top-level executives are not the only mature workers now in demand (Business Day, June 21). At the New York City Department for the Aging, we train job seekers 55 and older in computer skills and customer service and find that employers are eager to hire them.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Older top-level executives are not the only mature workers now in demand (Business Day, June 21). At the New York City Department for the Aging, we train job seekers 55 and older in computer skills and customer service and find that employers are eager to hire them.</p>
        <p>More than 90 percent of our graduates get jobs. Mature workers can master the latest technology, know what customer service really means, and are good examples for younger employees.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL S. RABIN  Deputy Commissioner  Department for the Aging  New York, June 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
